const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What are BCAAs and why do they matter for recovery?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'BCAAs (Branched-Chain Amino Acids) are three essential amino acids — leucine, isoleucine, and valine — that your body cannot produce on its own. They comprise approximately 35% of the essential amino acids in muscle protein. Leucine is the primary driver of muscle protein synthesis (MPS), the process that repairs and rebuilds muscle fibers after exercise. BCAAs reduce exercise-induced muscle damage, decrease delayed-onset muscle soreness (DOMS), and support recovery between training sessions. A 2:1:1 ratio of leucine to isoleucine to valine is the most studied and recommended ratio.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do BCAA gummies work as well as BCAA powder?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'BCAA gummies deliver the same amino acids as powder but typically at lower total doses per serving (1-3g vs 5-10g in powder). The amino acids themselves are absorbed identically regardless of format. For casual gym-goers and those seeking general recovery support, the doses in gummies are adequate. For competitive athletes training at high volumes, BCAA powder may be more practical to achieve the 5-10g doses used in clinical studies. Gummies excel in convenience and compliance — they taste better and require no mixing.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'When should I take BCAA gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'For optimal results, take BCAA gummies 30 minutes before exercise (to elevate blood amino acid levels before training), during prolonged exercise sessions (to reduce muscle breakdown during training), or within 30 minutes after exercise (to kickstart recovery). If you can only take them once, post-workout is the most impactful timing. On rest days, take BCAAs with a meal to support ongoing muscle repair. Consistency matters more than perfect timing — daily intake provides cumulative recovery benefits.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do I need BCAAs if I already take protein?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'If you consume adequate protein (0.7-1g per pound of body weight daily) from complete protein sources, you are likely getting sufficient BCAAs from your diet. However, BCAAs can still benefit you in specific scenarios: training in a fasted state (BCAAs prevent muscle breakdown without breaking a fast as significantly as a full protein serving), very high training volumes (extra BCAAs reduce accumulated muscle damage), or caloric deficits (BCAAs help preserve lean mass during cutting phases). BCAAs are most beneficial for people who struggle to hit daily protein targets.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the ideal BCAA ratio?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The most studied and recommended ratio is 2:1:1 (leucine:isoleucine:valine). This ratio mirrors the natural proportion found in muscle tissue and provides enough leucine to activate the mTOR pathway for muscle protein synthesis while maintaining adequate isoleucine and valine for energy metabolism and recovery. Some products use 4:1:1 or 8:1:1 ratios with higher leucine, but clinical evidence does not consistently show these are superior to 2:1:1. The 2:1:1 ratio remains the evidence-based standard.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are BCAA gummies safe?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'BCAAs are among the most extensively studied sports supplements and are considered safe for healthy adults at recommended doses (3-10g daily). They are naturally present in all protein-containing foods. Side effects are rare but can include nausea at very high doses. People with maple syrup urine disease (MSUD) must avoid BCAA supplements entirely. Those with kidney or liver disease should consult their physician before supplementing. Pregnant or nursing women should also consult their healthcare provider before using BCAA supplements.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How long does it take for BCAAs to work?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'BCAAs are absorbed rapidly — blood amino acid levels peak within 30-60 minutes of ingestion. Acute effects on reducing perceived exertion and muscle soreness can be noticed within the first few training sessions. Cumulative recovery benefits (reduced DOMS, faster recovery between sessions) typically become noticeable after 1-2 weeks of consistent daily use. Muscle preservation benefits during caloric deficits or high-volume training phases emerge over 4-8 weeks. As with all supplements, consistency of daily intake matters more than any single dose.' },
    },
  ],
};
