    <h2 id="why-bcaa">Why BCAAs Matter for Muscle Recovery and Performance</h2>

    <p>Branched-Chain Amino Acids — leucine, isoleucine, and valine — are three of the nine essential amino acids your body cannot synthesize on its own. Unlike other amino acids that are metabolized primarily in the liver, BCAAs are oxidized directly in skeletal muscle tissue, making them uniquely available as fuel during exercise and uniquely important for post-exercise recovery. Leucine, in particular, activates the mTOR signaling pathway — the master switch for muscle protein synthesis (MPS) — which initiates the repair and growth of muscle fibers damaged during resistance training or intense exercise.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">35%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of the essential amino acids in muscle protein are BCAAs. A meta-analysis of 8 randomized controlled trials published in the <em>Journal of the International Society of Sports Nutrition</em> found that BCAA supplementation <strong>reduced exercise-induced muscle damage by 22% and delayed-onset muscle soreness (DOMS) by up to 33%</strong> compared to placebo.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The gummy format makes BCAA supplementation accessible for people who dislike the bitter taste of unflavored BCAA powder or the inconvenience of mixing drinks. While gummies typically deliver lower total BCAA doses (1-3.5g per serving versus 5-10g in powder), this range is sufficient for general recovery support, especially when combined with adequate dietary protein intake. For competitive athletes requiring higher doses, gummies can supplement powder use for convenience during travel or on-the-go situations.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Leucine — The MPS Trigger</strong>
        <p>Leucine is the most potent activator of the mTOR pathway, which initiates muscle protein synthesis. A minimum leucine threshold of approximately 2-3g per meal or serving is needed to maximally stimulate MPS. This is why the 2:1:1 ratio prioritizes leucine content.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Isoleucine — Energy & Glucose Uptake</strong>
        <p>Isoleucine enhances glucose uptake into muscle cells during exercise, providing a secondary fuel source and helping maintain blood sugar stability during prolonged training sessions. It also contributes to immune function recovery after strenuous exercise.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Valine — Anti-Fatigue</strong>
        <p>Valine competes with tryptophan for transport across the blood-brain barrier, reducing serotonin production during exercise. This mechanism delays central nervous system fatigue, helping you train harder and longer before mental exhaustion sets in.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>The 2:1:1 Ratio — Clinical Standard</strong>
        <p>The 2:1:1 leucine-to-isoleucine-to-valine ratio is the most studied in clinical trials. It mirrors the natural BCAA proportion in skeletal muscle and delivers enough leucine to activate MPS while maintaining adequate isoleucine and valine for energy and anti-fatigue effects.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

